
                                                          FLATMAP
_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

                                                          EASY (1-10)
                                                         --------------

(1) Extracting Hashtags from Tweets? 
Input:  
List<String> tweets = Arrays.asList( 
"I love #Java", 
"Programming in #Python is great" 
); 
Output: [#Java, #Python] 
 

(2) Flattening Nested Lists of Integers?
Input: 
 List<List<Integer>> data = Arrays.asList(
                Arrays.asList(1, 2),
                Arrays.asList(3, 4),
                Arrays.asList(5)
        ); 
Output: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]


(3) Flattening Nested Lists of Strings? 
Input: 
        List<List<String>> data = Arrays.asList(
                Arrays.asList("apple", "banana"),
                Arrays.asList("cherry"),
                Arrays.asList("date")
        );
Output: [apple, banana, cherry, date] 

(4) Mapping and Flattening to Integer Lists? 
Input: 
        List<List<String>> data = Arrays.asList(
                Arrays.asList("1", "2"),
                Arrays.asList("3"),
                Arrays.asList("4")
        );
Output: [1, 2, 3, 4] 


(5) Flattening a List of Optional Values? 
Input: 
        List<List<Optional<String>>> data = Arrays.asList(
                Arrays.asList(Optional.of("a")),
                Arrays.asList(Optional.empty()),
                Arrays.asList(Optional.of("b"))
        );
Output: [a, b] 

(6) Flattening a List of Lists with Different Sizes? 
Input: 
    List<List<Integer>> list = Arrays.asList(
            Arrays.asList(1), 
            Arrays.asList(2, 3, 4), 
            Arrays.asList(5, 6));
Output: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]


(7) Flattening a List of Characters? 
Input:
    List<List<Character>> list = Arrays.asList(
            Arrays.asList('a', 'b'),
            Arrays.asList('c', 'd')
    );
Output: [a, b, c, d] 

(8) Flattening and Removing Duplicates?
Input: 
    List<List<Integer>> list = Arrays.asList(
            Arrays.asList(1, 2),
            Arrays.asList(2, 3),
            Arrays.asList(3, 4)
    );
Output: [1, 2, 3, 4] 


(9) Flattening Nested Maps? 
Input: 
List<Map<String, List<Integer>>> data = Arrays.asList(
        new HashMap<String, List<Integer>>() {{
            put("a", Arrays.asList(1, 2));
        }},
        new HashMap<String, List<Integer>>() {{
            put("b", Arrays.asList(3, 4));
        }}
);
Output: [1, 2, 3, 4] 


(10)   Flattening a List of Lists of Booleans? 
Input: 
List<List<Boolean>> data = Arrays.asList(
        Arrays.asList(true, false),
        Arrays.asList(false, true)
);
Output: [true, false, false, true] 


                                                                MEDIUM (1-10)
                                                             -----------------------

(1) Flattening a List of Lists and Converting to Strings? 
Input: 
    List<List<Integer>> list = Arrays.asList(
            Arrays.asList(1, 2),
            Arrays.asList(3, 4)
    );
Output: [1, 2, 3, 4] 

(2) Flattening and Summing Nested Lists of Integers? 
Input: 
    List<List<Integer>> list = Arrays.asList(
            Arrays.asList(1, 2),
            Arrays.asList(3, 4)
    );
Output: 10 

(3) Flattening a List of Student Subjects? 
Input:
    List<List<Student>> list = Arrays.asList(
            Arrays.asList(new Student("John",Arrays.asList("Math", "Science"))),
            Arrays.asList(new Student("Jane",Arrays.asList("English")))
    );
Output: [Math, Science, English] 
 

(4) Flattening a List of JSON Objects having id and tags? 
Input: 
    List<List<Student>> list = Arrays.asList(
            Arrays.asList(new Student(1, Arrays.asList("java", "spring"))),
            Arrays.asList(new Student(2, Arrays.asList("python", "django")))
    );
Output: ["java", "spring", "python", "django"]

(5) Flattening a List of Mixed Data Types? 
Input: 
    List<List<Object>> list = Arrays.asList(
            Arrays.asList(1, "a"),
            Arrays.asList(2, "b"),
            Arrays.asList(3, "c")
    );
Output: [1, a, 2, b, 3, c] 

(6) Flattening a List of Paths? 
Input:
    List<List<String>> list = Arrays.asList(
            Arrays.asList("/home/user"),
            Arrays.asList("/etc"),
            Arrays.asList("/var/log")
    );
Output: [/home/user, /etc, /var/log] 


(7) Flattening a List of Recipes with Ingredients? 
Input:  
List<Recipe> recipes = Arrays.asList(
        new Recipe("Cake", Arrays.asList("flour", "sugar")),
        new Recipe("Pasta", Arrays.asList("noodles", "sauce"))
);
Output: [flour, sugar, noodles, sauce] 



                                                                HARD (1-10)
                                                              -----------------

(1) Flattening Nested Optional Values? 
Input: 
    List<Optional<List<Integer>>> list = Arrays.asList(
            Optional.of(Arrays.asList(1, 2)),
            Optional.empty(),
            Optional.of(Arrays.asList(3, 4))
    );
Output: [1, 2, 3, 4] 


(2) Flattening a List of Maps with Multiple Entries? 
Input:
    List<Map<String, List<String>>> list = Arrays.asList(

            new HashMap<String, List<String>>() {{
                put("key1", Arrays.asList("val1", "val2"));
            }},

            new HashMap<String, List<String>>() {{
                put("key2", Arrays.asList("val3"));
            }}
    );
Output: [val1, val2, val3] 



(3) Flattening a List of Product Attributes? 
Input: 
    List<Product> products = Arrays.asList(

            new Product(
                    "Laptop",
                    Arrays.asList("16GB RAM", "512GB SSD")
            ),

            new Product(
                    "Phone",
                    Arrays.asList("128GB", "5G")
            )
    );
Output: ["16GB RAM", "512GB SSD", "128GB", "5G"] 


(4) Flattening Nested Hierarchical Data? 
Input: 
    List<List<Item>> data = Arrays.asList(
            Arrays.asList(
                    new Item(1, "A"),
                    new Item(2, "B")
            ),
            Arrays.asList(
                    new Item(3, "C")
            ));
Output: [A{id=1, name='A'}, A{id=2, name='B'}, A{id=3, name='C'}] 

